突厥阿史那氏，蓋古匈奴北部也．居金山之陽，臣于蠕蠕，種裔繁衍．至吐門，遂彊大{A14B}{A14B}隋大業之亂，始畢可汗咄吉嗣立，華人多往依之，契丹、室韋、吐谷渾、高昌皆役屬（新唐書）

"本東胡種，其先為匈奴所破，保鮮卑山．{A14B}{A14B}逃潢水之南，黃龍之北．至元魏，自號曰契丹{A14B}{A14B}其君大賀氏，有勝兵四萬，析八部，臣于突厥（新唐書）；古匈奴之種也（舊五代史）；契丹自後魏以來，名見中國．或曰與庫莫奚同類而異種{A14B}{A14B}得鮮卑之故地，故又以為鮮卑之遺種{A14B}{A14B}後分為八部，其一曰伹皆利部，二曰乙室活部，三曰實活部，四曰納尾部，五曰頻沒部，六曰內會雞部，七曰集解部，八曰奚嗢部（新五代史），四庫本作後分為八部，其一曰達爾扎部，二曰伊斯琿部，三曰舎琿部，四曰諾爾威部，五曰頗摩部，六曰納古齊部，七曰濟勒勤部，八曰實衮部. C. Atwood note:Kitan (this is conventional Chinese transcription dating from the Tang, for what in Mongolian is usually Kitad)"

Ethnicity code 3;其先匈奴之裔也，在後魏時，號鐵勒部落．其微小，其俗驍強，依託高車，臣屬突厥，近謂之特勒（舊唐書）；其先匈奴也，俗多乘高輪車，元魏時亦號高車部，或曰敕勒，訛為鐵勒．其部落曰袁紇、薛延陀、契苾羽、都播、骨利幹、多覽葛、僕骨、拔野古、同羅、渾、思結、斛薛、奚結、阿跌、白霫，凡十有五種，皆散處磧北（新唐書）；其先匈奴之種也．後魏時，號為鐵勒，亦名回紇．唐元和四年，本國可汗遣使上言，改為回鶻，義取迴旋搏擊，如鶻之迅捷也（舊五代史）；本匈奴之別裔，在天德西北娑陵水上．後魏號鐵勒，唐初號特勒，後稱回紇（宋史）

"C. Atwood note:Uriyangqad (singular: Uriyangqan) was/is a surname among the Mongols. Distinguish from “Uriyangqai” is a general term used by steppe Mongols for all forest peoples to the northwest (roughly Tuva, Altay Republic, Minusinsk Basin, etc.), and carries slightly pejorative implications of being cultural exotic and politically weak. The 合/哈 character at the end (the two are interchangeable in Yuan-era transcriptions, although not in Ming/Qing ones), would actually normally be capped by a diacritical –ti (惕 or perhaps 剔), for the final –d, which is usually omitted in common transcription. "

"C. Atwood note:Should be Che'üdei, which some identify with Je'üriyedei (also attested as Je’üredei). But this seems unlikely on phonological grounds (Cleaves did not make that association in his article on the Baljuna covenant). YS 132/3210 has 徹里臺; is the 里 an lapsus for 兀, or could it be added? The latter could make it徹兀里臺, which could Che’üridei, closer to Je’üredei , but simple lapsus seems to be more probable, since 徹兀里臺 is not actually attested. Whether this is a semuren or a Mongol surname appears very uncertain. The person with the name is Maili, which could be from Melik, which would indicate a Semuren. But he “led the徹里臺tribe” in 1203 which should indicate his group was as a whole present on the Mongolian plateau before the conquest."
